com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Will there ever be Mecha?</span><hr size=1> Your still thinking within the realm in which you live.  In the next 20 years I highly doubt we would build something the size of the popular gundam.  I would say, the mecha wouldn't be used for warfare at all either, I'd say it'd be used as a construction bot, weilding a torch, nail gun, and the strength needed to life up heavy objects.  <br><br>Infantry needs to stay mobile, even now with their overweight limit, you are still pushing the limits of the infantry.  They need to be fast, small, and lethal, anything bigger only takes away your speed and size.  However, power suits would work, if they where extremely mobile.  Meaning, it could bends in all the places a human bends, they need to get down on the ground quick to hide, etc etc.  Anything else is a tank with legs.  Imagine a suit walking towards you, that couldn't crouch, duck, laydown, and what not, it just stood up.  It would be attacked all the time, it's like it's just standing out to be shot.<br><br>Now, I'd say...within the next 200+ years you'd see mecha's.  The ones they are producing today are much smaller scale, so the ones later one would be their much larger cousins.<br><br>I'd have to agree about the controls, why have joysticks and all that when you can link it up to the human brain.  You would then go on to complain about all the complex procedures needed to maintain the mech right?  Well think about the human body.  Humans use 10% of their brain.  And almost all of your bodily functions are done without thinking, like digesting food, focusing eyes, analyzing smells, using your liver, blah blah blah, all that.  If you where to make it so that all the functions of a mecha where 2nd nature to a human, you wouldn't have to worry about joysticks and all that.  Think out of the realm of the 21st century and into the possible future.<br><br>However, I think it is much harder to build a 